1
00:00:36,386 --> 00:00:37,745
That's right.

2
00:00:38,785 --> 00:00:39,986
New York.

3
00:00:40,706 --> 00:00:42,347
It's 1958.

4
00:00:44,067 --> 00:00:46,628
Anyway, for a few more minutes it is.

5
00:00:47,588 --> 00:00:50,628
Come midnight, it's going to be 1959.

6
00:00:51,389 --> 00:00:53,588
A whole other feeling.

7
00:00:53,628 --> 00:00:55,109
The New Year.

8
00:00:55,909 --> 00:00:57,109
The future.

9
00:00:58,390 --> 00:01:02,190
Old Daddy Earth fixing to start
one more trip around the sun.

10
00:01:02,950 --> 00:01:06,071
Everybody hoping this ride round
be a little more giddy...

11
00:01:06,872 --> 00:01:08,271
...a little more gay.

12
00:01:08,991 --> 00:01:12,392
All over town, champagne corks
is a-popping.

13
00:01:13,352 --> 00:01:17,913
Over in the Waldorf, the big shots is
dancing to the strains of Guy Lombardo.

14
00:01:19,234 --> 00:01:24,074
In Times Square, the little folks is watching
and waiting for that big ball to drop.

15
00:01:25,674 --> 00:01:29,115
They're all trying to catch hold
of one moment of time...

16
00:01:29,715 --> 00:01:31,155
...to be able to say:

17
00:01:31,395 --> 00:01:33,155
"Right now! This is it!

18
00:01:33,995 --> 00:01:35,036
I got it!"

19
00:01:37,196 --> 00:01:39,155
Of course, by then it'll be past.

20
00:01:39,755 --> 00:01:41,356
But they're all happy...

21
00:01:42,116 --> 00:01:44,117
...everybody having a good time.

22
00:01:45,157 --> 00:01:46,678
Well, almost everybody.

23
00:01:47,998 --> 00:01:50,998
There's a few lost souls
floating around out there.

24
00:01:53,359 --> 00:01:55,479
Now, if y'all ain't from the city...

25
00:01:55,919 --> 00:01:58,359
...we got something here
called "the rat race".

26
00:01:59,440 --> 00:02:03,440
Got a way of chewing folks up
so that they don't want no celebrating...

27
00:02:03,840 --> 00:02:05,641
...don't want no cheering up.

28
00:02:06,001 --> 00:02:08,242
Don't care nothing about no New Year's.

29
00:02:09,281 --> 00:02:10,441
Out of hope...

30
00:02:10,722 --> 00:02:12,002
...out of rope...

31
00:02:12,162 --> 00:02:13,402
...out of time.

32
00:02:15,042 --> 00:02:16,963
This here is Norville Barnes.

33
00:02:18,803 --> 00:02:20,684
That office he's stepping out of...

34
00:02:20,764 --> 00:02:23,845
...is the office of the president
of Hudsucker Industries.

35
00:02:24,524 --> 00:02:25,844
That's his office.

36
00:02:27,244 --> 00:02:28,804
How'd he get so high?

37
00:02:29,765 --> 00:02:31,725
And why's he feeling so low?

38
00:02:33,445 --> 00:02:35,166
Is he really going to do it?

39
00:02:35,846 --> 00:02:39,006
Is Norville really going
to jelly up the sidewalk?

40
00:02:40,645 --> 00:02:42,006
Well, the future...

41
00:02:42,486 --> 00:02:45,047
...that's something you can
never tell about.

42
00:02:46,167 --> 00:02:47,368
But the past...

43
00:02:49,688 --> 00:02:51,288
...that's another story.

44
00:05:07,911 --> 00:05:10,351
So in the third quarter
we saw no signs of weakening.

45
00:05:10,431 --> 00:05:13,752
We're up 18%%% over last year's
third-quarter gross...

46
00:05:13,992 --> 00:05:16,352
...and that, needless to say,
is a new record.

47
00:05:16,432 --> 00:05:20,753
Our competition continues to flag
and we continue to take up the slack.

48
00:05:21,193 --> 00:05:23,714
Market shares in most divisions
is increasing...

49
00:05:23,794 --> 00:05:26,715
...and we have opened
seven new regional offices.

50
00:05:27,155 --> 00:05:28,594
Our international division...

51
00:05:28,674 --> 00:05:32,715
...is also showing vigorous signs of upward
movement for the last six months...

52
00:05:32,875 --> 00:05:35,955
...and we're looking
at some exciting things in R&D.

53
00:06:14,482 --> 00:06:17,802
Sub-franchising. Don't talk to me
about sub-franchising.

54
00:06:17,962 --> 00:06:20,242
We're making so much money
in sub-franchising...

55
00:06:20,322 --> 00:06:21,883
...it isn't even funny.

56
00:06:22,163 --> 00:06:26,204
Our nominees and assigns continue
to multiply and expand...

57
00:06:26,284 --> 00:06:29,804
...extending our influence nationally
and abroad.

58
00:06:29,964 --> 00:06:32,324
Our owned and operateds are performing...

59
00:06:32,364 --> 00:06:35,485
...far beyond our expectations
both here and abroad.

60
00:06:35,605 --> 00:06:38,085
And the Federal Tax Act of 1958...

61
00:06:38,285 --> 00:06:41,886
...is giving us a swell write-off
on our plant and heavies.

62
00:07:06,210 --> 00:07:09,891
And our last debenture issue
was this year's fastest seller.

63
00:07:10,411 --> 00:07:12,772
So, third quarter and year-to-date...

64
00:07:13,012 --> 00:07:16,932
...we have set a new record in sales,
a new record in gross...

65
00:07:17,012 --> 00:07:19,532
...a new record in pre-tax earnings...

66
00:07:19,732 --> 00:07:22,493
...a new record in after-tax profits...

67
00:07:22,733 --> 00:07:25,534
...and our stock has split twice
in the past year.

68
00:07:25,894 --> 00:07:26,934
In short...

69
00:07:31,494 --> 00:07:32,854
...we're loaded.

70
00:08:23,503 --> 00:08:24,943
Mr. Hudsucker?

71
00:10:06,160 --> 00:10:08,560
It's a pity to waste a whole Monte Cristo.

72
00:10:09,440 --> 00:10:10,920
He could've opened the window.

73
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:13,761
Waring Hudsucker never did anything
the easy way.

74
00:10:14,321 --> 00:10:17,281
Why? Why did he do it?
Everything was going so well.

75
00:10:18,081 --> 00:10:20,882
What am I, a headshrinker?
Maybe the man was unhappy.

76
00:10:21,042 --> 00:10:22,722
He didn't look unhappy.

77
00:10:22,882 --> 00:10:26,683
-He didn't look rich.
-He was never an easy man to figure out.

78
00:10:27,203 --> 00:10:29,724
He built this company with his bare hands.

79
00:10:30,364 --> 00:10:32,484
Every step he took was a step up...

80
00:10:33,524 --> 00:10:35,284
...except, of course, this last one.

81
00:10:35,364 --> 00:10:37,245
He was a swell fella...

82
00:10:38,045 --> 00:10:41,805
...but when the president, chairman
and owner of 87% of the stock...

83
00:10:41,885 --> 00:10:42,966
...drops...

84
00:10:43,606 --> 00:10:44,646
...44 floors...

85
00:10:44,726 --> 00:10:45,446
45.

86
00:10:45,526 --> 00:10:46,806
Counting the mezzanine.

87
00:10:46,966 --> 00:10:49,606
Then the company, too, has a problem.
Stillson!

88
00:10:51,766 --> 00:10:54,247
What exactly is the disposition
of Waring's stock?

89
00:10:54,407 --> 00:10:55,688
As you know...

90
00:10:55,768 --> 00:10:57,928
...Hud left no will and no family.

91
00:10:58,008 --> 00:11:00,968
The company bylaws are quite clear
in that event.

92
00:11:01,049 --> 00:11:04,329
"His entire portfolio will be converted
into common stock...

93
00:11:04,489 --> 00:11:08,650
"...and will be sold over the counter
as of the first of the fiscal year...

94
00:11:08,770 --> 00:11:10,770
-"...following his demise".
-Meaning?

95
00:11:11,130 --> 00:11:14,651
Meaning simply that Waring's stock
and control of the company...

96
00:11:14,771 --> 00:11:17,771
...will be made available
to the public January 1st.

97
00:11:19,452 --> 00:11:20,852
Do you mean to say...

98
00:11:21,052 --> 00:11:24,492
...that any slob in a smelly T-shirt
will be able to buy Hudsucker stock?

99
00:11:24,812 --> 00:11:26,813
The company bylaws are quite clear.

100
00:11:26,893 --> 00:11:28,854
My God! You're animals!

101
00:11:28,934 --> 00:11:33,014
How can you discuss his stock
when the man has just leapt 45 floors?

102
00:11:33,054 --> 00:11:33,894
44.

103
00:11:33,974 --> 00:11:35,534
Not counting the mezzanine.

104
00:11:35,614 --> 00:11:36,734
Quit showboating.

105
00:11:36,774 --> 00:11:39,135
The man is gone. The question now
is whether we'll let...

106
00:11:39,175 --> 00:11:42,095
...John Q. Public waltz in here
and buy our company.

107
00:11:42,175 --> 00:11:44,136
What are you suggesting?

108
00:11:44,216 --> 00:11:47,096
Certainly we can't afford
to buy a controlling interest.

109
00:11:47,336 --> 00:11:49,335
Not while the stock is this strong.

110
00:11:50,336 --> 00:11:52,656
How soon before Hud's paper
hits the market?

111
00:11:52,736 --> 00:11:53,537
January 1st.

112
00:11:53,577 --> 00:11:54,937
-Thirty days.
-Four weeks.

113
00:11:54,977 --> 00:11:56,898
-A month at the most.
-One month...

114
00:11:56,978 --> 00:11:59,138
...to make the blue-chip investment
of the century...

115
00:11:59,218 --> 00:12:01,378
...look like a round-trip ticket
on the Titanic.

116
00:12:01,418 --> 00:12:04,058
We play up the fact that Hud is dead.

117
00:12:04,138 --> 00:12:05,539
Long live the Hud!

118
00:12:05,619 --> 00:12:06,659
We depress the stock.

119
00:12:06,739 --> 00:12:09,380
-To the point where we can buy 50%.
-51%.

120
00:12:09,420 --> 00:12:10,740
Not counting the mezzanine.

121
00:12:10,820 --> 00:12:11,740
It could work.

122
00:12:11,820 --> 00:12:13,220
-It should work.
-It would work.

123
00:12:13,260 --> 00:12:14,901
It's working already.

124
00:12:16,061 --> 00:12:18,901
Waring Hudsucker is abstract art
on Madison Avenue.

125
00:12:20,021 --> 00:12:24,262
What we need now is a new president
who will inspire panic in the stockholder.

126
00:12:24,422 --> 00:12:25,782
-A puppet!
-A proxy!

127
00:12:25,862 --> 00:12:26,783
A pawn!

128
00:12:29,223 --> 00:12:30,304
Some jerk...

129
00:12:30,904 --> 00:12:32,705
...we can really push around.

130
00:12:34,584 --> 00:12:38,184
You punch in at 8:30 every a.m.,
at 7:30 a.m. following a business holiday...

131
00:12:38,224 --> 00:12:40,225
...unless it's a Monday, then it's 8:00.

132
00:12:40,305 --> 00:12:43,785
-Punch in late and they dock you.
-This goes to seven! Urgent.

133
00:12:43,825 --> 00:12:47,386
Incoming articles get a voucher.
Outgoing articles provide a voucher.

134
00:12:47,466 --> 00:12:49,785
Move any article without a voucher,
they dock you!

135
00:12:49,865 --> 00:12:52,186
Take this up to the secretarial pool
on three! ASAP!

136
00:12:52,266 --> 00:12:54,827
Letter-size, a green voucher!
Folder-size, a yellow voucher!

137
00:12:54,867 --> 00:12:56,387
Parcel-size, a maroon voucher!

138
00:12:56,467 --> 00:12:58,468
This is for Morgatross! Chop-chop!

139
00:12:58,508 --> 00:13:00,668
Wrong color voucher and they dock you!

140
00:13:01,508 --> 00:13:03,869
6-7-8-7-0-4-9-Alpha-6!

141
00:13:04,149 --> 00:13:07,149
That is your employee number!
It will not be repeated!

142
00:13:07,349 --> 00:13:09,750
Without it, you can't cash your paycheck.

143
00:13:09,830 --> 00:13:11,470
All right! This goes up to 27!

144
00:13:11,550 --> 00:13:14,390
Return a waiver!
Do not return without a signed waiver!

145
00:13:14,470 --> 00:13:18,432
Inter-office mail is code 37!
Intra-office mail is 37-3.

146
00:13:18,592 --> 00:13:20,751
Outside mail is 3-37.

147
00:13:20,911 --> 00:13:22,632
Code it wrong and they dock you!

148
00:13:22,672 --> 00:13:25,432
I was supposed to have this on 28
ten minutes ago!

149
00:13:25,752 --> 00:13:30,153
This has been your orientation.
Is there anything you do not understand?

150
00:13:30,353 --> 00:13:33,715
If you have not been fully orientated,
you must file a complaint!

151
00:13:33,795 --> 00:13:36,634
File a faulty complaint, and they dock you!

152
00:13:41,955 --> 00:13:42,915
Kloppitt.

153
00:13:43,075 --> 00:13:45,876
Kloppitt, Kloppitt, Kloppitt, Kloppitt....

154
00:13:45,916 --> 00:13:47,316
Max Kloppitt.

155
00:13:47,396 --> 00:13:49,556
"Max Kloppitt, Jr".

156
00:13:57,797 --> 00:14:00,918
What do you do when the envelope
is too big for the slot?

157
00:14:02,198 --> 00:14:04,359
If you fold them, they fire you.

158
00:14:06,478 --> 00:14:07,959
I usually throw them out.

159
00:14:14,280 --> 00:14:15,720
Just got hired today.

160
00:14:16,201 --> 00:14:17,081
Terrific.

161
00:14:17,841 --> 00:14:18,801
Entry level.

162
00:14:21,801 --> 00:14:22,762
But...

163
00:14:23,402 --> 00:14:24,762
...I got big ideas.

164
00:14:25,442 --> 00:14:26,722
I'm sure you do.

165
00:14:27,202 --> 00:14:28,363
For instance...

166
00:14:29,483 --> 00:14:30,683
...look at this sweet baby.

167
00:14:34,445 --> 00:14:35,885
I developed it myself.

168
00:14:35,964 --> 00:14:38,284
Yes, sirree, this is my ticket upstairs.

169
00:14:41,805 --> 00:14:43,165
You know, for kids.

170
00:14:44,125 --> 00:14:45,045
Terrific.

171
00:14:46,125 --> 00:14:49,006
So, you see. I won't be working
in the mail room long.

172
00:14:49,086 --> 00:14:50,926
No, I don't guess you will be.

173
00:14:52,125 --> 00:14:53,646
How long've you been here?

174
00:14:53,726 --> 00:14:54,926
Forty-eight years.

175
00:14:55,406 --> 00:14:57,647
Next year they move me up to parcels...

176
00:14:58,687 --> 00:14:59,968
...if I'm lucky.

177
00:15:02,128 --> 00:15:03,968
Attention Hudsucker employees:

178
00:15:04,368 --> 00:15:08,009
We regretfully announce
that at 30 seconds after the hour of noon...

179
00:15:08,129 --> 00:15:09,329
...Hudsucker time...

180
00:15:09,409 --> 00:15:11,970
...Waring Hudsucker, Founder, President...

181
00:15:12,210 --> 00:15:15,010
...and Chairman of the Board
of Hudsucker Industries...

182
00:15:15,090 --> 00:15:16,530
...merged with the infinite.

183
00:15:16,810 --> 00:15:19,171
To mark this occasion of corporate loss...

184
00:15:19,251 --> 00:15:23,212
...we ask that all employees observe
a moment of silent contemplation.

185
00:15:30,053 --> 00:15:31,933
Thank you for your kind attention.

186
00:15:32,133 --> 00:15:35,014
This moment has been duly noted
on your timecards...

187
00:15:35,134 --> 00:15:38,214
...and will be deducted from your pay.
That is all.

188
00:15:41,455 --> 00:15:42,615
Blue letter!

189
00:15:42,775 --> 00:15:43,895
Blue letter!

190
00:15:43,975 --> 00:15:45,655
They're bringing a blue letter!

191
00:16:18,381 --> 00:16:19,781
It's a blue letter.

192
00:16:20,541 --> 00:16:21,742
Top, top level.

193
00:16:22,422 --> 00:16:24,782
Confidential communication
between the brass.

194
00:16:25,702 --> 00:16:27,022
Usually bad news.

195
00:16:27,902 --> 00:16:29,742
They hate blue letters upstairs.

196
00:16:33,744 --> 00:16:34,744
Hate them.

197
00:16:34,824 --> 00:16:35,624
You!

198
00:16:36,144 --> 00:16:37,505
Yeah, you! Barnes!

199
00:16:38,064 --> 00:16:39,264
You don't look busy!

200
00:16:39,824 --> 00:16:41,784
Think you can handle a blue letter?

201
00:16:41,864 --> 00:16:46,305
This letter was sent this morning
by the big man himself, Waring Hudsucker!

202
00:16:46,545 --> 00:16:49,986
It's addressed to Sid Mussburger,
Hudsucker's right-hand man!

203
00:16:50,146 --> 00:16:51,586
It's a blue letter!

204
00:16:51,986 --> 00:16:54,866
That means you got to put it right
in Mussburger's hands.

205
00:16:55,026 --> 00:16:57,226
No secretaries! No receptionists!

206
00:16:57,426 --> 00:16:59,587
No colleagues! No excuses!

207
00:17:00,507 --> 00:17:01,668
Mussburger!

208
00:17:03,508 --> 00:17:07,509
Hi! My name's Buzz, I got the fuzz,
I make the elevator do what she does.

209
00:17:08,269 --> 00:17:09,428
Hang it up to dry.

210
00:17:09,508 --> 00:17:11,349
-What's your pleasure?
-Fourty-four.

211
00:17:11,509 --> 00:17:14,310
Forty-four, the top-brass floor.
Say, buddy...

212
00:17:14,470 --> 00:17:18,070
...what takes 50 years to get to
the top floor and 30 seconds to get down?

213
00:17:18,310 --> 00:17:20,471
Waring Hudsucker! You get it, buddy?

214
00:17:20,791 --> 00:17:23,991
Say, buddy! Mr. Kline, up to nine.
Mrs. Dell, Personnel.

215
00:17:24,111 --> 00:17:25,992
-Mr. Levin, 37.
-Thirty-six.

216
00:17:26,072 --> 00:17:27,112
Walk down!

217
00:17:27,192 --> 00:17:28,872
Ladies and gentlemen,
please step to the rear.

218
00:17:28,952 --> 00:17:30,952
Here comes the gargantuan Mr. Grier.

219
00:17:33,233 --> 00:17:36,394
Buddy, who's the most liquid businessman
on the street?

220
00:17:36,474 --> 00:17:37,755
Waring Hudsucker.

221
00:17:38,395 --> 00:17:41,874
When is the sidewalk fully dressed?
When it's wearing Hudsucker!

222
00:17:43,074 --> 00:17:43,995
You get it?

223
00:17:44,075 --> 00:17:47,395
It's a pun, a knee-slapper,
a play on Jesus, Joseph and Mary....

224
00:17:47,515 --> 00:17:48,915
Is that a blue letter?

225
00:17:48,955 --> 00:17:52,956
Why didn't you tell a guy? Hold on, folks,
we're express to the top floor!

226
00:18:07,718 --> 00:18:08,999
Good luck, buddy.

227
00:18:12,199 --> 00:18:13,439
You'll need it.

228
00:18:25,841 --> 00:18:27,442
Mr. Mussburger's office?

229
00:19:22,451 --> 00:19:23,451
Hello.

230
00:19:24,372 --> 00:19:26,611
Do you have an appointment?

231
00:19:28,212 --> 00:19:30,172
Shall we look in the book?

232
00:19:32,332 --> 00:19:35,053
-We don't seem to be in the book.
-I wouldn't be.

233
00:19:35,213 --> 00:19:38,694
If we had an appointment,
we'd be in the book.

234
00:19:39,214 --> 00:19:40,375
I have this....

235
00:19:40,934 --> 00:19:42,134
Oh, here it is.

236
00:19:47,695 --> 00:19:48,615
Gambotz?

237
00:19:49,495 --> 00:19:50,695
Harry Gambotz?

238
00:19:50,895 --> 00:19:53,376
No, too risky.
He's green but he's not slow.

239
00:19:54,856 --> 00:19:55,856
Who is he?

240
00:19:56,175 --> 00:19:58,936
No, I want an imbecile,
not a cipher, or you'd have the job.

241
00:20:01,297 --> 00:20:03,057
They moved him to grommets and O-rings.

242
00:20:03,097 --> 00:20:04,458
He's doing pretty well.

243
00:20:05,778 --> 00:20:07,378
No, not McClanahan.

244
00:20:08,338 --> 00:20:11,258
He bungled the Teleyard merger
so he's got something to prove.

245
00:20:11,538 --> 00:20:12,779
Who let you in?

246
00:20:13,459 --> 00:20:16,380
Atwater? Tremendous.
Except I just fired him last week.

247
00:20:17,060 --> 00:20:18,180
Mr. Mussburger...

248
00:20:18,260 --> 00:20:20,180
...Mr. Bumstead's waiting downstairs.

249
00:20:20,300 --> 00:20:22,421
-I'll be right there.
-Yes, Mr. Mussburger.

250
00:20:22,461 --> 00:20:23,541
Spit it out!

251
00:20:25,502 --> 00:20:27,861
Maybe you're
the company's biggest moron.

252
00:20:28,102 --> 00:20:31,582
We can't use Morris. Been here too long.
He's a nice guy with too many friends.

253
00:20:31,662 --> 00:20:34,543
In fact, why don't you fire him?
Scratch that, I'll fire him.

254
00:20:35,103 --> 00:20:36,543
Make it fast. Fast!

255
00:20:37,023 --> 00:20:38,904
Mr. Bumstead is growing restless.

256
00:20:38,984 --> 00:20:41,345
Tell him I'll be right there.
Give him a magazine.

257
00:20:41,425 --> 00:20:42,864
What are you, a mute?

258
00:20:44,504 --> 00:20:45,784
How's the stock?

259
00:20:45,904 --> 00:20:47,905
Bad? Well, it's not bad enough.

260
00:20:48,545 --> 00:20:49,665
Listen, chump.

261
00:20:49,745 --> 00:20:53,786
Either you find me a ding-dong or tender
your key to the executive washroom.

262
00:20:53,866 --> 00:20:56,586
That goes double for you, pal.
Earclay? Oodgay!

263
00:21:01,146 --> 00:21:03,427
This better be good. I'm in a bad mood.

264
00:21:04,507 --> 00:21:07,828
Sir, I've got something for you
from the mail room, but first...

265
00:21:07,868 --> 00:21:12,708
...if I could take a minute of your very
valuable time to show you something...

266
00:21:12,788 --> 00:21:15,749
...I've been working on
for the past two or three years.

267
00:21:22,830 --> 00:21:24,191
You know, for kids.

268
00:21:25,031 --> 00:21:27,871
It's perfect for Hudsucker,
not that I'm any great genius.

269
00:21:27,911 --> 00:21:31,912
They say inspiration is 99% perspiration
and in my case it's at least twice that...

270
00:21:31,992 --> 00:21:34,872
-...but I've got to tell you, sir...
-Wait a minute!

271
00:22:17,639 --> 00:22:18,800
Sit down, son.

272
00:22:21,600 --> 00:22:22,560
Go ahead.

273
00:22:24,401 --> 00:22:25,441
Try it on.

274
00:22:38,443 --> 00:22:39,724
Put your feet up.

275
00:22:43,485 --> 00:22:44,444
Go ahead.

276
00:22:46,564 --> 00:22:48,885
Let's get to know one another, shall we?

277
00:22:50,765 --> 00:22:51,885
Let's chat...

278
00:22:55,126 --> 00:22:56,126
...man-to-man.

279
00:23:03,126 --> 00:23:05,367
You're from the basement, aren't you?

280
00:23:06,528 --> 00:23:08,488
And weren't blessed with much...

281
00:23:10,608 --> 00:23:11,728
...education?

282
00:23:12,128 --> 00:23:14,328
Well, I am a college graduate.

283
00:23:14,808 --> 00:23:17,289
But you did not excel in your studies.

284
00:23:17,369 --> 00:23:19,210
Well, I made the dean's list...

285
00:23:20,210 --> 00:23:22,650
...at the Muncie College
of Business Administration.

286
00:23:24,010 --> 00:23:26,651
And your friends called you "jerk",
didn't they?

287
00:23:28,212 --> 00:23:29,132
"Dope?"

288
00:23:29,252 --> 00:23:30,131
"Dipstick?"

289
00:23:30,171 --> 00:23:31,612
"Lamebrain?" "Schmo?"

290
00:23:31,692 --> 00:23:32,892
Not even behind your back?

291
00:23:32,972 --> 00:23:35,452
They voted me "Most Likely to Succeed".

292
00:23:35,532 --> 00:23:36,692
You're fired.

293
00:23:38,853 --> 00:23:42,054
Get your feet off my desk,
get out of my office.

294
00:23:42,614 --> 00:23:44,215
Leave your apron in the locker room.

295
00:23:44,734 --> 00:23:45,694
Oh, my God!

296
00:23:45,814 --> 00:23:50,015
The Bumstead contracts. I've been
working on that deal for four years!

297
00:23:50,175 --> 00:23:52,175
Get out of here! I'll take care of it!

298
00:23:53,015 --> 00:23:56,096
You could have destroyed
the most sensitive document of my career.

299
00:23:56,176 --> 00:23:58,576
Mr. Bumstead is threatening to leave.

300
00:23:58,696 --> 00:23:59,975
I'm on my way down.

301
00:24:00,055 --> 00:24:03,376
We need the first page of the contract
retyped with copies going to Legal.

302
00:24:03,456 --> 00:24:04,977
Yes, Mr. Mussburger.

303
00:24:08,698 --> 00:24:10,178
Out! Out of the office!

304
00:24:12,858 --> 00:24:14,019
Down three points?

305
00:24:14,099 --> 00:24:16,418
That's encouraging. How about New York?

306
00:24:17,539 --> 00:24:19,299
Not that way, through the door!

307
00:24:19,940 --> 00:24:22,580
It'll take three hours to retype
the Bumstead contracts.

308
00:24:22,620 --> 00:24:23,700
Where are you going?

309
00:24:23,780 --> 00:24:25,420
Get out! Stop that!

310
00:24:25,700 --> 00:24:27,221
Mr. Bumstead's threatening to leave.

311
00:24:27,301 --> 00:24:29,742
Not the whole contract, just the first page.

312
00:24:30,022 --> 00:24:32,022
I'll be there. Give him another magazine.

313
00:24:32,062 --> 00:24:34,622
-He says he'll leave.
-I said I'll be there!

314
00:24:35,702 --> 00:24:39,143
Up on your feet! We don't crawl here
at Hudsucker Industries!

315
00:24:39,543 --> 00:24:41,304
-My leg is on fire!
-No assumptions!

316
00:24:41,344 --> 00:24:44,905
It's early yet. Just let me know
where we stand at the closing bell.

317
00:24:53,985 --> 00:24:56,105
Oh, my God, the Bumstead contracts!

318
00:25:01,345 --> 00:25:03,226
No magazines! No coffee!

319
00:25:03,426 --> 00:25:07,787
Mussburger! I want to see Mussburger!
Or did he jump out a window too?

320
00:25:08,828 --> 00:25:12,308
Don't worry, Mr. Mussburger, I got you!
I got you by your pants.

321
00:25:15,109 --> 00:25:15,989
Pants?

322
00:25:20,389 --> 00:25:24,150
Mr. Mussburger, I'm gonna give
your pants a nice double stitch.

323
00:25:24,590 --> 00:25:28,191
It'll make them real strong
and you're going to look real sharp.

324
00:25:29,031 --> 00:25:31,431
No. Single stitch is fine.

325
00:25:31,631 --> 00:25:33,872
But the double stitch lasts forever.

326
00:25:35,032 --> 00:25:37,512
Why on earth would I want
a double stitch?

327
00:25:38,752 --> 00:25:40,153
To pad your account.

328
00:25:40,553 --> 00:25:42,034
Single stitch is fine.

329
00:25:48,114 --> 00:25:49,154
Damn!

330
00:25:55,515 --> 00:25:58,716
What the heck! Mr. Mussburger
is such a nice man...

331
00:25:59,076 --> 00:26:01,556
...I'm going to give him
a double stitch anyway.

332
00:26:02,635 --> 00:26:05,836
That's some strong stitch, you bet!

333
00:27:47,895 --> 00:27:49,934
"The Einstein of Enterprise".

334
00:27:50,934 --> 00:27:52,374
"The Edison of Industry".

335
00:27:53,575 --> 00:27:55,655
"The Billion-Dollar Cranium! "

336
00:27:57,455 --> 00:27:58,935
"Idea Man! "

337
00:28:00,736 --> 00:28:02,976
And not one of you has given me
a story on him!

338
00:28:03,016 --> 00:28:04,695
Bunch of lamebrains!

339
00:28:05,135 --> 00:28:07,696
Facts, figures, charts.
They never sold a newspaper!

340
00:28:07,856 --> 00:28:09,737
I read this morning's Argus
and let me tell you something:

341
00:28:09,817 --> 00:28:11,337
I'd wrap a fish in it!

342
00:28:11,418 --> 00:28:12,978
I'd use it as kindling!

343
00:28:13,058 --> 00:28:17,258
I'd train my poodle on it if he wasn't
a French poodle and partial to Paris Soir.

344
00:28:17,418 --> 00:28:20,178
But I wouldn't pay a nickel
to read the thing!

345
00:28:20,258 --> 00:28:22,219
Come on, Chief, give us a break.

346
00:28:22,819 --> 00:28:24,820
Sure, Tibbs. Take a break.

347
00:28:25,540 --> 00:28:27,580
Go to Florida. Lie in the sun.

348
00:28:28,180 --> 00:28:30,541
Wait for a coconut to drop.
File a story on it.

349
00:28:30,861 --> 00:28:34,022
It'd be more of a grabber than your piece
on the county grain surplus!

350
00:28:34,102 --> 00:28:36,502
The human angle!
That's what sells papers!

351
00:28:36,862 --> 00:28:40,182
We need a front page with a heart
and the ldea Man can put it there!

352
00:28:40,262 --> 00:28:41,662
If we had more access...

353
00:28:41,702 --> 00:28:44,103
If a frog had wings
it wouldn't bump it's ass hopping.

354
00:28:44,183 --> 00:28:46,144
I don't want excuses, I want results!

355
00:28:46,544 --> 00:28:49,105
What makes the ldea Man tick?
Where's he from?

356
00:28:49,225 --> 00:28:52,664
I want to know everything about him!
Has he got a girl? Has he got parents?

357
00:28:52,744 --> 00:28:54,705
Everybody has parents.

358
00:28:54,865 --> 00:28:56,465
All right, how many?

359
00:28:57,545 --> 00:28:59,705
How about it, Parkinson?
You've been awfully quiet.

360
00:29:01,586 --> 00:29:02,986
Still waters run deep.

361
00:29:03,066 --> 00:29:05,465
Only thing deep with Parkinson
are the holes in his ears.

362
00:29:05,545 --> 00:29:07,106
Yes! ldea Man!

363
00:29:07,706 --> 00:29:10,827
What are his hopes and dreams,
his desires and aspirations?

364
00:29:11,107 --> 00:29:13,708
Does he think all the time
or a certain portion of the day?

365
00:29:13,748 --> 00:29:17,188
How tall is he? Where does he sleep?
What does he have for breakfast?

366
00:29:17,228 --> 00:29:19,389
Does he put jam on his toast
or doesn't he?

367
00:29:19,469 --> 00:29:21,428
If not, why not and since when?

368
00:29:22,389 --> 00:29:23,349
Well?

369
00:29:24,630 --> 00:29:26,110
You're useless.

370
00:29:26,830 --> 00:29:28,030
Yes. Idea Man.

371
00:29:28,670 --> 00:29:29,630
"Creator".

372
00:29:29,710 --> 00:29:30,711
"Innovator".

373
00:29:30,991 --> 00:29:32,271
"Cerebrator".

374
00:29:32,911 --> 00:29:33,912
Fake!

375
00:29:34,512 --> 00:29:36,471
I tell you, the guy's a phony.

376
00:29:36,551 --> 00:29:37,992
-Phony?
-As a $3 bill.

377
00:29:38,072 --> 00:29:39,672
-Says who?
-Says me, Amy Archer!

378
00:29:39,752 --> 00:29:41,992
Why is he an ldea Man?
Because Hudsucker says so?

379
00:29:42,032 --> 00:29:44,553
What are his ideas?
Why can't anyone interview him?

380
00:29:44,633 --> 00:29:46,634
Five bucks says she mentions her Pulitzer.

381
00:29:47,474 --> 00:29:49,355
Again? You're on.

382
00:29:49,435 --> 00:29:51,314
Look at the mug on this guy.

383
00:29:51,354 --> 00:29:54,394
The jutting eyebrows, the simian forehead,
the idiotic grin.

384
00:29:54,474 --> 00:29:56,275
He has a face only a mother could love...

385
00:29:57,635 --> 00:29:58,595
...on payday.

386
00:29:58,835 --> 00:30:01,676
The only story here is
how this guy made a monkey out of you.

387
00:30:01,716 --> 00:30:04,236
Like it or not, I'm still editor of this rag.

388
00:30:04,436 --> 00:30:07,396
I thought you were writing,
"J. Edgar Hoover: When Will He Marry?"

389
00:30:07,476 --> 00:30:10,557
-I filed it yesterday. Nice tie, Earl.
-Well, do a follow-up.

390
00:30:10,677 --> 00:30:12,637
"Hoover: Crimebuster or Pantywaist?"

391
00:30:12,717 --> 00:30:15,798
The rest of you mugs get some brains
and get me that ldea Man story!

392
00:30:17,398 --> 00:30:18,558
He's the bunk.

393
00:30:24,439 --> 00:30:26,200
I'll stake my Pulitzer on it!

394
00:30:28,640 --> 00:30:30,600
Say, buddy, where'd you get the new duds?

395
00:30:30,680 --> 00:30:33,481
Say, buddy, how did Old Bucketbutt
like his blue letter?

396
00:30:34,041 --> 00:30:37,081
Did he bust a gut? Did he die?
Well, hello, Mr. Mussburger.

397
00:30:37,121 --> 00:30:38,522
Lobby, we haven't got all day.

398
00:30:38,562 --> 00:30:40,282
Right away, Mr. Mussburger.

399
00:30:40,402 --> 00:30:42,362
How're you this fine morning, sir?

400
00:30:43,122 --> 00:30:45,403
It's been a pleasure serving you today, sir.

401
00:30:45,443 --> 00:30:48,004
It's been a pleasure serving you too, buddy.

402
00:30:48,164 --> 00:30:51,724
Shouldn't we be a little concerned
with the downward spiral of our stock...

403
00:30:51,804 --> 00:30:53,084
...these past few days?

404
00:30:53,164 --> 00:30:55,724
You're the expert,
but at the Muncie College of Business...

405
00:30:55,804 --> 00:30:57,445
Relax, it's only natural...

406
00:30:57,605 --> 00:31:01,005
...in a period of transition for
the more timid element to run for cover.

407
00:31:01,085 --> 00:31:04,606
Like I said, you're the expert
but do you remember the plan I outlined...

408
00:31:04,686 --> 00:31:07,725
...the day I set fire to your....
The day I was promoted?

409
00:31:08,125 --> 00:31:12,127
I do remember and I was impressed.
But that's all forgotten now.

410
00:31:14,207 --> 00:31:15,328
Thank you, Sid.

411
00:31:16,128 --> 00:31:19,568
The reason I mention it is it requires
such a small capital investment....

412
00:31:19,648 --> 00:31:22,768
-There's a huge potential profit...
-Damn it, where's my car?

413
00:31:22,848 --> 00:31:25,729
...given the demographics boom
of the burgeoning middle-class.

414
00:31:25,809 --> 00:31:29,690
So if you agree, I'd like to bounce the idea
off a few people at lunch.

415
00:31:29,770 --> 00:31:30,730
Sure.

416
00:31:30,970 --> 00:31:34,691
Tell whoever you want.
I'd like to hear about it at some point too.

417
00:31:43,652 --> 00:31:44,933
I got gas, Benny.

418
00:31:46,493 --> 00:31:47,773
Tell me about it.

419
00:31:48,214 --> 00:31:50,374
No kidding, Benny. I got gas.

420
00:31:51,175 --> 00:31:52,574
You get the special?

421
00:31:52,934 --> 00:31:54,014
Far from it.

422
00:31:57,855 --> 00:31:59,055
Enter the dame.

423
00:31:59,815 --> 00:32:01,695
There's one in every story.

424
00:32:02,295 --> 00:32:04,776
Ten bucks says she's looking for a handout.

425
00:32:05,096 --> 00:32:07,855
Twenty bucks says not here,
she don't find one.

426
00:32:08,455 --> 00:32:10,016
She's looking for her mark.

427
00:32:10,096 --> 00:32:11,256
She finds him.

428
00:32:11,336 --> 00:32:13,857
She sits down and orders...

429
00:32:15,177 --> 00:32:16,458
...a light lunch.

430
00:32:16,938 --> 00:32:19,058
How will she pay for this lunch?

431
00:32:19,498 --> 00:32:21,218
She looks through her purse.

432
00:32:21,499 --> 00:32:22,499
No money.

433
00:32:22,938 --> 00:32:24,579
The mark notices.

434
00:32:25,939 --> 00:32:27,580
He's not noticing, Benny.

435
00:32:27,660 --> 00:32:29,020
Maybe he's wise.

436
00:32:29,420 --> 00:32:30,820
He don't look wise.

437
00:32:32,940 --> 00:32:34,101
Plan two.

438
00:32:34,421 --> 00:32:36,141
Here come the waterworks.

439
00:32:36,461 --> 00:32:38,461
-Yellowstone.
-Old Faithful.

440
00:32:38,541 --> 00:32:40,302
Hello, Niagara.

441
00:32:40,742 --> 00:32:41,862
He notices.

442
00:32:41,902 --> 00:32:43,262
She's distressed.

443
00:32:43,502 --> 00:32:44,862
He's concerned.

444
00:32:45,422 --> 00:32:47,423
She explains her predicament.

445
00:32:47,783 --> 00:32:48,744
And....

446
00:32:49,384 --> 00:32:51,304
Enter the light lunch.

447
00:32:52,465 --> 00:32:54,464
She's got other problems, of course.

448
00:32:54,544 --> 00:32:56,344
There's illness in the family.

449
00:32:56,784 --> 00:32:59,545
-Her mother needs an operation.
-Urgently.

450
00:32:59,705 --> 00:33:01,305
-Adenoids.
-No, Benny.

451
00:33:02,585 --> 00:33:03,986
Lumbago.

452
00:33:04,706 --> 00:33:06,946
That gag's got whiskers on it.

453
00:33:08,066 --> 00:33:09,585
He ain't biting, Benny.

454
00:33:09,665 --> 00:33:12,386
-She's losing him, Lou.
-Maybe he's wise.

455
00:33:12,986 --> 00:33:14,627
He don't look wise.

456
00:33:15,187 --> 00:33:17,828
-How does she pull this out?
-He's getting away.

457
00:33:17,908 --> 00:33:19,388
She better think fast.

458
00:33:19,708 --> 00:33:20,988
She isn't.

459
00:33:21,308 --> 00:33:22,709
She is!

460
00:33:23,749 --> 00:33:25,068
She's good, Benny.

461
00:33:25,669 --> 00:33:27,109
She's damn good, Lou.

462
00:33:28,430 --> 00:33:30,430
Can I get you boys anything else?

463
00:33:32,630 --> 00:33:33,750
Bromo.

464
00:33:34,551 --> 00:33:35,631
Bromo.

465
00:33:37,552 --> 00:33:41,152
I'm sorry we had to take the stairs.
It was just that horrible elevator boy!

466
00:33:41,232 --> 00:33:44,192
I can't say how much I appreciate
your listening to my story.

467
00:33:44,272 --> 00:33:48,513
I'm lucky to find someone in this bustling
city with a stout heart and a ready ear.

468
00:33:49,073 --> 00:33:51,274
There I was, travelling
through this great country.

469
00:33:51,354 --> 00:33:53,595
Some I met were kind to me,
others exceedingly cruel.

470
00:33:53,675 --> 00:33:55,994
Traveling by motor bus, rail,
even by thumb....

471
00:33:56,034 --> 00:33:57,394
The couch, please.

472
00:33:57,514 --> 00:34:00,795
Hoarding every dollar, counting
every nickel, pinching every penny.

473
00:34:01,035 --> 00:34:03,635
It's been a long road leading
to the coffee shop downstairs.

474
00:34:03,675 --> 00:34:06,916
Not that I'd trade a day, an hour,
a moment of it for anything.

475
00:34:07,236 --> 00:34:08,756
I don't know what came over me.

476
00:34:08,836 --> 00:34:11,035
I guess it was the shock of eating
after so long...

477
00:34:11,116 --> 00:34:13,396
...without the enzymes kicking in
after so long....

478
00:34:17,358 --> 00:34:20,838
Then you couldn't possibly know
what it is to be tired and hungry.

479
00:34:21,038 --> 00:34:22,038
Hungry, anyway.

480
00:34:22,078 --> 00:34:25,078
I don't want to bore you with details
of my life. It's not happy.

481
00:34:25,158 --> 00:34:27,519
Suffice to say I'm jobless,
but not for want of trying.

482
00:34:27,559 --> 00:34:31,040
I'm friendless, with no one to take care
of me and had you not come along...

483
00:34:31,120 --> 00:34:33,720
-...exactly when you did....
-I, myself...

484
00:34:33,840 --> 00:34:35,721
I arrived in town not ten days ago...

485
00:34:35,801 --> 00:34:38,882
...full of dreams, anxious to make my way
in the world...

486
00:34:38,922 --> 00:34:41,602
...a little naive perhaps,
but armed with determination...

487
00:34:41,682 --> 00:34:44,202
...a solid work ethic,
and an indomitable belief in the future...

488
00:34:44,282 --> 00:34:46,082
-I, myself...
-...only to have that belief...

489
00:34:46,162 --> 00:34:49,363
...that unsullied optimism, dashed against
the marble of the workplace.

490
00:34:49,443 --> 00:34:52,364
Such is life. Seek and ye shall find.
Work and ye shall prosper.

491
00:34:52,444 --> 00:34:54,045
-Cigarette?
-No, thank you.

492
00:34:54,125 --> 00:34:56,364
Seek and ye shall find,
work and ye shall prosper.

493
00:34:56,444 --> 00:34:59,084
These were the watchwords,
the ethos of my education...

494
00:34:59,164 --> 00:35:00,605
...the values instilled in me...

495
00:35:00,645 --> 00:35:03,845
...while I was growing up in a town
you've probably never heard of.

